# Frontend JS — Required Patterns per Page File

Every page-level JS file in `ui/static/js/` must include these three local helpers and follow the rules below. Zero TypeScript/JSDoc errors expected.

## 1. `escapeHtml()` — XSS Prevention with Decode-First

**CRITICAL**: The backend's `html.escape()` + `bleach.clean()` combination double-encodes entities: `'` → `&#x27;` (html.escape) → `&amp;#x27;` (bleach escapes the `&`). To prevent rendering `&#x27;` literally, `escapeHtml()` must decode `&amp;` FIRST, then the named entities, then re-encode.

```javascript
/**
 * @param {string|null|undefined} str
 * @returns {string}
 */
function escapeHtml(str) {
    if (str == null) return '';
    // Decode &amp; first so &amp;#x27; → &#x27; → '
    // (bleach double-encodes & in entities from Python's html.escape output)
    const decoded = String(str)
        .replace(/&amp;/g, '&')
        .replace(/&#x27;/g, "'")
        .replace(/&#039;/g, "'")
        .replace(/&quot;/g, '"')
        .replace(/&lt;/g, '<')
        .replace(/&gt;/g, '>');
    return decoded
        .replace(/&/g, '&amp;').replace(/</g, '&lt;').replace(/>/g, '&gt;')
        .replace(/"/g, '&quot;').replace(/'/g, '&#039;');
}
```

Apply to **every dynamic value** in template literals: `` `<span>${escapeHtml(value)}</span>` ``

**Never decode in a different order** — always `&amp;` first, then named entities (`&#x27;`, `&#039;`, etc.), then `&amp;` last. Reversing the order leaves `&amp;#x27;` unresolved and renders the entity literally as text.

## 1b. `decodeEntities()` — For `.textContent` Assignments

When setting `.textContent` (not `.innerHTML`), the browser does not interpret HTML entities — `&#039;` will display literally. Use a separate decode-only helper for any server-rendered string assigned via `.textContent`:

```javascript
/** Decode HTML entities for use with .textContent (no re-encoding step) */
function decodeEntities(str) {
    if (str == null) return '';
    return String(str)
        .replace(/&amp;/g, '&')
        .replace(/&#x27;/g, "'")
        .replace(/&#039;/g, "'")
        .replace(/&quot;/g, '"')
        .replace(/&lt;/g, '<')
        .replace(/&gt;/g, '>');
}

// Usage:
el.textContent = decodeEntities(job.job_title || 'Job Application');  // ✅
el.textContent = job.job_title;                                        // ❌ shows &amp; literally
el.innerHTML   = escapeHtml(job.job_title);                            // ✅ (innerHTML path)
```

## 2. `getAuthToken()` — Token Retrieval

```javascript
/**
 * @returns {string|null}
 */
function getAuthToken() {
    // @ts-ignore
    return (window.app && typeof window.app.getAuthToken === 'function')
        ? window.app.getAuthToken()
        : (localStorage.getItem('access_token') || localStorage.getItem('authToken'));
}
```

## 3. `notify()` — Notifications

```javascript
/**
 * @param {string} msg
 * @param {'success'|'error'|'warning'|'info'} [type]
 */
function notify(msg, type = 'info') {
    // @ts-ignore
    if (window.app && window.app.showNotification) { window.app.showNotification(msg, type); return; }
    const c = document.getElementById('alertContainer');
    if (!c) return;
    const d = document.createElement('div');
    d.className = `alert alert-${type === 'error' ? 'danger' : type} alert-dismissible fade show`;
    d.innerHTML = `${escapeHtml(msg)}<button type="button" class="btn-close" data-bs-dismiss="alert"></button>`;
    c.appendChild(d); setTimeout(() => d.remove(), 5000);
}
```

## Key Rules

### API Calls
- JSON calls → `window.app.apiCall('/api/v1/...')` (handles 401 refresh automatically)
- Binary/blob downloads → raw `fetch()` with `getAuthToken()`
- **Parse FastAPI errors with `errData.message || errData.detail`** — the custom `APIError` system returns `message`; standard FastAPI validation errors return `detail`; always check both:

```javascript
const errData = await response.json().catch(() => ({}));
throw new Error(errData.message || errData.detail || 'Fallback error message');
```

### `localStorage.clear()` — Always Preserve `cookie_consent`
Only account deletion uses `localStorage.clear()`. All other logouts use targeted `removeItem`. When `clear()` is needed, save and restore `cookie_consent`:

```javascript
// ✅ Correct — preserves cookie consent banner state
const cc = localStorage.getItem('cookie_consent');
localStorage.clear();
if (cc) localStorage.setItem('cookie_consent', cc);
window.location.href = '/auth/login?account_deleted=1';

// ❌ Wrong — wipes cookie consent, banner reappears on every page
localStorage.clear();
window.location.href = '/';
```

### `btn-primary` Uses the App Gradient — Not Bootstrap Blue
`btn-primary` is globally overridden in `app.css` to use `var(--accent-gradient)` (cyan→purple). Do not re-define it per-page. The same applies to `btn-outline-primary` (uses `var(--accent-primary)` for border/text).

### Confirmation Dialogs — Never Use Native `confirm()` / `prompt()`
All destructive/confirmation flows must use `window.showConfirm()` from `ui/static/js/confirm-modal.js`, which is loaded globally via `base.html` on every page.

```javascript
// ✅ Correct — custom modal, consistent design, works in e2e tests
const confirmed = await window.showConfirm({
    title: 'Delete Application',
    message: 'This action cannot be undone.',
    confirmText: 'Delete',
    type: 'danger',            // 'danger' | 'warning' | 'primary'
});
if (!confirmed) return;

// With text input (e.g. type "DELETE" to confirm, or password entry)
const value = await window.showConfirm({
    title: 'Confirm',
    message: 'Type DELETE to confirm.',
    confirmText: 'Confirm',
    type: 'danger',
    inputPlaceholder: 'Type DELETE to confirm',
    inputType: 'text',         // or 'password'
});
if (value !== 'DELETE') return;

// ❌ Wrong — native browser dialog, unstyled, blocks e2e automation
if (!confirm('Are you sure?')) return;
const pw = prompt('Enter password:');
```

`showConfirm()` returns:
- `null` — user cancelled
- `true` — confirmed (no input field)
- `string` — input field value (may be empty string)

CSS lives in `app.css` (`.confirm-modal`, `.confirm-modal-input`). The modal uses `var(--bg-card)`, `var(--border-color)`, `var(--text-primary)` — consistent with the dark theme.

### Event Handling
- No `onclick=` in static HTML or dynamic strings
- Use event delegation on stable parent + `data-action` / `data-id` attributes

### Timers
- Module-level timer IDs: `let _myTimer = /** @type {number|null} */ (null);`
- Clear before setting: `if (_myTimer !== null) clearTimeout(_myTimer);`
- Clean up in `beforeunload` listener

### In-Flight Guards
```javascript
let _submitting = false;
async function handleSubmit() {
    if (_submitting) return;  // ← before any await
    _submitting = true;
    try { /* ... */ } finally { _submitting = false; }
}
```

### Null Safety
```javascript
const el = /** @type {HTMLInputElement|null} */ (document.getElementById('myInput'));
if (!el) return;
el.value = 'hello';
```

### Catch Blocks (strict mode)
```javascript
} catch (error) {
    const err = /** @type {Error} */ (error);
    notify(err.message || 'Failed', 'error');
}
```

### Event Bus Constants
Always use `window.BusEvents.EVENT_NAME`, never raw strings like `'application:created'`.

### Date Arithmetic
```javascript
const diff = new Date().getTime() - new Date(dateStr).getTime(); // ✅
// NOT: new Date() - new Date(dateStr) // ❌ TS error
```

### Open Redirect Prevention
Before assigning any URL from `urlParams.get(...)` or an API response to `window.location.href`, validate it is a relative path:

```javascript
const raw = urlParams.get('redirect') || response['redirect'];
// ✅ Only allow: starts with / but NOT //
const safeRedirect = (raw && /^\/(?!\/)/.test(raw)) ? raw : null;
window.location.href = safeRedirect || '/dashboard';
```

Never redirect to an absolute URL derived from user input — it enables open-redirect attacks.

### URL Parameter Encoding
Always `encodeURIComponent()` dynamic values in URLs, including in `href` attributes and WebSocket query strings:

```javascript
// ✅ Correct
`/application/${encodeURIComponent(sessionId)}/download`
`?token=${encodeURIComponent(token)}`

// ❌ Wrong — unescaped value could break URL or allow injection
`/application/${sessionId}/download`
```

### Never Use `style=` HTML Attributes
All inline `style="..."` HTML attributes are blocked by the CSP `style-src` policy. Instead:

- **Visibility toggling**: use `.is-hidden` class (from `app.css`). JS shows elements with `element.style.display = 'block'` (fine — JS inline styles are not governed by `style-src` CSP).
- **Layout helpers**: use `.flex-1`, `.cursor-pointer` from `app.css`.
- **Color helpers**: use `.text-accent`, `.text-secondary`, `.text-muted`, `.font-mono-inline` from `app.css`.
- **Page-specific styles**: add a CSS class to the page's `<style nonce="...">` block.
- **Truly dynamic values** (e.g. `element.style.width = percent + '%'`): set via JS — this is allowed.

When JS sets `element.style.display = 'block'` it overrides `.is-hidden { display: none; }` because the class has no `!important`. This is the intended behaviour.

### `target="_blank"` Links — Require `rel`
Every link that opens in a new tab must include `rel="noopener noreferrer"`:

```html
<!-- ✅ Correct -->
<a href="https://external.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Link</a>
```

Without `rel="noopener"`, the opened page can access `window.opener` and redirect the parent tab.

### Password Field Clearing
Always clear the password input field immediately after a login attempt (success or failure):

```javascript
DOM.passwordField.value = '';  // in both success path and catch block
```

This prevents the value remaining in the DOM where it could be read by XSS or exposed if the back button is used.

### `app.js` Is NOT Loaded on Dashboard Pages
`app.js` (the `JobApplicationAssistant` class) is only loaded on `ui/index.html` (the landing page). It is **not** in `base.html`, so `window.app` is `undefined` on all dashboard pages.

Dashboard page scripts (`dashboard-home.js`, etc.) already check `window.app` and delegate to it when present. But they must **not rely on `app.js` for global navbar events** — they must set up their own document-level listeners.

The most important case is the **logout button**. The navbar renders `<button data-action="logout">` on every dashboard page. Each dashboard JS file must wire this up itself:

```javascript
// Required in every dashboard page script — wire navbar logout independently of app.js
document.addEventListener('click', (e) => {
    const target = /** @type {Element|null} */ (e.target);
    const actionEl = /** @type {HTMLElement|null} */ (target?.closest('[data-action]'));
    if (actionEl?.dataset['action'] === 'logout') {
        e.preventDefault();
        logout(); // local logout() function in the same file
    }
});
```

The local `logout()` function should delegate to `window.app.logout()` when available, and fall back to clearing localStorage + redirecting:

```javascript
function logout() {
    // @ts-ignore
    if (window.app && typeof window.app.logout === 'function') { window.app.logout(); return; }
    localStorage.removeItem('access_token');
    localStorage.removeItem('authToken');
    window.location.href = (window.APP_CONFIG && window.APP_CONFIG.loginUrl) || '/auth/login';
}
```

### Text Sanitization — Allow All Unicode

`sanitizeText()` in `profile-setup.js` strips only ASCII control characters. **Never** restrict to a hardcoded ASCII allowlist — this would silently strip Unicode bullet symbols (`■`, `▪`, `▸`, `–`, `—`, etc.) that the LLM uses in parsed descriptions.

```javascript
// ✅ Correct — strips control chars only, allows all printable ASCII + Unicode
return text.replace(/[\x00-\x08\x0B\x0C\x0E-\x1F\x7F]/g, '');

// ❌ Wrong — strips ■, ▪, –, —, accented chars, and any non-ASCII
return text.replace(/[^a-zA-Z0-9\s.,;:!?()\[\]\-'"•\n]/g, '');
```

The same pattern applies to the backend validators (`DESCRIPTION_PATTERN`, `PROFESSIONAL_NAME_PATTERN` in `api/profile.py`).

### Required numeric fields — `0` is valid

Profile **Years of Experience** (`years_experience`) may be **`0`** (students, career changers, first role). In JavaScript, **`0` is falsy** — never treat it as “missing”:

- **Saving (`saveBasicInfo`)** — After `parseInt`, do not use `if (!data[field])` for a mixed required-field list; `!0` is `true`. Parse to a number, then require `years_experience` with an explicit check (e.g. `Number.isNaN(parsed)` for empty/invalid, not `!parsed`).
- **Populating the form** — Use `value !== undefined && value !== null` (then `String(value)` for the input), **not** `if (profileData.years_experience)` — otherwise a saved **`0`** never appears in the field.

The API already allows zero (`BasicInfo` in `api/profile.py` uses `ge=0`).

### Multi-Step Form — Validate All Steps Before Saving

`completeProfile()` must validate **all steps upfront** before making any API calls. Running save → validate → save → validate in sequence means early steps save successfully while later validation errors confuse the user (spinner runs for seconds then fails).

```javascript
// ✅ Correct — validate everything first, navigate to first failing step
const stepValidations = [
    { step: 1, fn: validateBasicInfo },
    { step: 2, fn: validateWorkExperience },
    { step: 3, fn: validateEducation },
    { step: 4, fn: validateSkillsQualifications },
    { step: 5, fn: validateCareerPreferences },
];
for (const { step, fn } of stepValidations) {
    if (!fn()) {          // fn() shows its own error via showErrorMessage()
        changeStep(step); // navigate — does NOT clear the error message
        window.scrollTo({ top: 0, behavior: "smooth" });
        return;
    }
}
// All valid — now safe to setLoading(true) and save
```

### `profile-setup.js` — “No work experience” must be persisted

If the user checks **“I don’t have any relevant work experience yet”**, `saveWorkExperience()` must **`PUT /api/v1/profile/work-experience`** with `{ work_experience: [] }`. Returning success without that call leaves the column **`NULL`** in PostgreSQL, so `POST /profile/complete` still reports **Work Experience** as missing. Unchecked = require at least one valid entry (enforced by `validateWorkExperience()`). When loading profile data, keep the checkbox in sync when the saved list is empty.

### `profile-setup.js` — “No formal education” must be persisted

If the user checks **“I don't have formal education to add”**, `saveEducation()` must **`PUT /api/v1/profile/education`** with `{ education: [] }`. Skipping the API call leaves **`education` NULL**, so `POST /profile/complete` still reports **Education** incomplete. `[]` means the user explicitly completed step 3 with no schools (`_check_education_completion` treats `NULL` as incomplete and non-null `[]` as complete). See **`database-patterns.mdc`**.

### `changeStep()` Must NOT Clear Error Messages

`changeStep()` navigates between form steps. It must **not** hide the error alert — validation functions show their error first, then `changeStep()` is called to navigate to the failing step, and the error must remain visible after navigation.

```javascript
// ✅ Correct
function changeStep(newStep) {
    if (newStep < 1 || newStep > totalSteps) return;
    currentStep = newStep;
    updateStepDisplay();
    updateStepIndicators();
    updateProgressBar();
}

// ❌ Wrong — clears the error shown by the validator
function changeStep(newStep) {
    const errorAlert = document.getElementById("error-alert");
    if (errorAlert) errorAlert.classList.add("d-none"); // ← removes error before user sees it
    // ...
}
```

### WebSocket Reconnection — Exponential Backoff
WebSocket `onclose` handlers must not simply set `ws = null`. Implement reconnection with exponential backoff:

```javascript
const WS_MAX_RECONNECT_ATTEMPTS = 8;
let wsReconnectAttempts = 0;

ws.onclose = (event) => {
    const noRetry = [1000, 1008, 4001]; // intentional close, policy, auth failure
    if (!noRetry.includes(event.code) && wsReconnectAttempts < WS_MAX_RECONNECT_ATTEMPTS) {
        const delay = Math.min(1000 * Math.pow(2, wsReconnectAttempts), 30000);
        wsReconnectAttempts++;
        setTimeout(connectWs, delay);
    }
};
ws.onopen = () => { wsReconnectAttempts = 0; };
```
